More Frequency Response
=======================
	To show x(t)=e^(i\omega t) -> LTI -> y(t)=H(\omega)e^(i\omega t)

	H(\omega)e^(i\omega t)

	x(t)=cos(\omega t)-> LTI -> y(t)=|H(\omega)| cos(\omega t + \angle H(\omega))

	|H(\omega)\| is the \*gain\* of the system.

	\angle H(\omega) 

	\*Real Systems\* map real signals to real outputs.

	H(\omega) e^(i\omega t)
	=|H(\omega)| e^(i\omega t + \angle H(\omega))

	Linearity:
		x(t)------> sys ---------> y(t)
		ax(t)-----> sys ---------> ay(t) \forall a \in \complex

	Time Invariance:
		x(t)----------------> sys ---------> y(t)
		x'(t) = x(t - T)----> sys ---------> y'(t) = y(t-T)
	
	Show that:
		x(t)=e^(i\omega t)-----> LTI ----> y(t)?

		x'(t)=x(t-T) = e^(i\omega (t-T))-----> LTI -----> y'(t) = y(t-T) = e^(-i\omega T) y(t)

		y(t-T) = e^(-i\omega T) y(t) \foral t,T

		Claim y(t)=Ae^(i\omega t)
		y(0)=e^(-i\omega t)y(t)
		y(t)=y(0)e^(i\omega t)

	Example:
		H(\omega)=a_1 e^(i\omega \tau_1) + a_2 e^(i\omega \tau_2)
		
		Magnitude |H| is maximized when the complex numbers are aligned; \omega \tau_1 = \omega \tau_2 + 2\pi n, n \in \integers
		Maximum of a_1+a_2
		Magnitude |H| is minimized when the complex numbers are misaligned by 180 degrees. \omega \tau_1 = \omega \tau_2 + (2n+1)\pi, n \in \integers
		Minimum of a_1-a_2
